04584nam a22006375i 9780226552422DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265524227 a10.7208/97802265524222doi  a(DE-B1597)522574  a(OCoLC)1030993851  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aLC1091b.C97 2019 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a372.832231 aCurren, Randall, eauthor.10aPatriotic Education in a Global Age /cRandall Curren, Charles Dorn. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory and Philosophy of Education Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Americanizing Curricula -- tTwo. Heroes and Rituals -- tThree. Militarizing Schools, Mobilizing Students -- tFour. The Education We Need -- tFive. Cultivating Civic Virtue -- tSix. Global Civic Education -- tConclusion. Realizing America in a Global Age -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShould schools attempt to cultivate patriotism? If so, why? And what conception of patriotism should drive those efforts? Is patriotism essential to preserving national unity, sustaining vigorous commitment to just institutions, or motivating national service? Are the hazards of patriotism so great as to overshadow its potential benefits? Is there a genuinely virtuous form of patriotism that societies and schools should strive to cultivate?   In Patriotic Education in a Global Age, philosopher Randall Curren and historian Charles Dorn address these questions as they seek to understand what role patriotism might legitimately play in schools as an aspect of civic education. They trace the aims and rationales that have guided the inculcation of patriotism in American schools over the years, the methods by which schools have sought to cultivate patriotism, and the conceptions of patriotism at work in those aims, rationales, and methods. They then examine what those conceptions mean for justice, education, and human flourishing. Though the history of attempts to cultivate patriotism in schools offers both positive and cautionary lessons, Curren and Dorn ultimately argue that a civic education organized around three components of civic virtue-intelligence, friendship, and competence-and an inclusive and enabling school community can contribute to the development of a virtuous form of patriotism that is compatible with equal citizenship, reasoned dissent, global justice, and devotion to the health of democratic institutions and the natural environment. Patriotic Education in a Global Age mounts a spirited defense of democratic institutions as it situates an understanding of patriotism in the context of nationalist, populist, and authoritarian movements in the United States and Europe, and will be of interest to anyone concerned about polarization in public life and the future of democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aNationalismxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aPatriotismxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 4aaims of education. 4acivic virtue. 4adissent. 4aglobal cooperation. 4aimmigration. 4aliberal education. 4anationalism. 4apatriotism. 4apublic schools. 4awar. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aDorn, Charles, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226552422423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226552422.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles